---
import ToolPage from '../../layouts/ToolPage.astro'
import ImageToBase64Island from '../../islands/ImageToBase64Island'
import { getToolMeta } from '@devkits/core'

const meta = getToolMeta('image-to-base64')!
---

<ToolPage meta={meta}>
  <ImageToBase64Island client:load />

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-4">How to Use</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>
        Click <strong>Choose File</strong> or drag an image onto the drop zone to load it. The
        tool immediately converts the image to a Base64 string and shows both the raw string and
        a ready-to-use <code>data:</code> URI. Toggle between the two formats with the buttons
        above the output, then click <strong>Copy</strong> to put the result on your clipboard.
      </p>
      <p>
        Typical use cases include embedding small icons or logos directly in HTML or CSS to
        eliminate HTTP requests, storing images in JSON payloads for REST APIs that do not accept
        multipart form data, including image thumbnails in email templates, and encoding
        images for use in <code>&lt;img src="data:..."&gt;</code> tags inside Markdown or
        rich text editors that do not support file uploads.
      </p>
      <p>
        Conversion runs in your browser using the Canvas and FileReader APIs. Your image is
        never uploaded to any server.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Why would I convert an image to Base64?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Base64 encoding lets you embed binary image data directly inside a text-based format
          such as HTML, CSS, JSON, or XML. This eliminates a separate HTTP request for the image,
          which can improve performance for small assets like icons. It is also required when
          sending images through APIs or message queues that only accept text payloads.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Does Base64 encoding increase the file size of an image?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Yes, by approximately 33%. Base64 encodes every 3 bytes of binary data as 4 ASCII
          characters, so a 100 KB PNG becomes roughly 133 KB as a Base64 string. For large
          images this overhead outweighs the HTTP-request savings, which is why Base64 embedding
          is typically reserved for images smaller than a few kilobytes.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What is the difference between a Base64 string and a data URI?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          A Base64 string is just the raw encoded data. A data URI wraps it with a MIME type
          prefix in the format <code>data:&lt;mediatype&gt;;base64,&lt;data&gt;</code>, for
          example <code>data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0K...</code>. You need the full data URI
          to use the image as an <code>src</code> attribute or a CSS <code>url()</code> value;
          the raw string alone is not sufficient.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">Which image formats are supported?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Any image format your browser can display is supported, including PNG, JPEG, GIF,
          WebP, SVG, and AVIF. The MIME type is detected automatically from the file and
          included in the generated data URI so the browser knows how to interpret the data.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ToolPage>
